# .github/CODEOWNERS — module ownership map (Dabbler module-organized projects).
#
# Scaffolded by the Dabbler AI Orchestration extension. GitHub requests a
# review from the matching owners whenever a PR touches their paths (later
# rules win over earlier ones). Docs:
# https://docs.github.com/articles/about-code-owners
#
# HOW TO ADAPT THIS FILE (keep it in sync with docs/modules.yaml):
#
#   1. One rule per module: map each module's `codeRoots` (and its
#      docs/modules/<slug>/ plan folder) to the module's owner(s).
#   2. Shared conflict-magnets get everyone: docs/modules.yaml itself,
#      CI workflows, and any root config several modules depend on.
#   3. The integration `touches` rule is a PROCESS, not a path rule:
#      CODEOWNERS can only match paths, so for a PR that changes an
#      integration module (one with a `touches:` list in docs/modules.yaml),
#      the reviewers must ensure the owners of EVERY touched module are
#      added as reviewers — the integration module composes their code, so
#      each named module's owner reviews. Encode what you can with path
#      rules on the integration module's codeRoots (list every touched
#      module's owner on that rule, as the example below shows), and treat
#      the rest as review discipline.
#
# WORKED EXAMPLE — a three-person team (uncomment and adapt):
# Priya owns `greeter`, Sam owns `clock`, and Alex owns `integration`
# with `touches: [greeter, clock]` — so the integration rule names all
# three: Alex as the owner, Priya and Sam because their modules are
# composed there.
#
# services/greeter/          @priya-gh
# docs/modules/greeter/      @priya-gh
#
# services/clock/            @sam-gh
# docs/modules/clock/        @sam-gh
#
# services/integration/      @alex-gh @priya-gh @sam-gh
# docs/modules/integration/  @alex-gh @priya-gh @sam-gh
#
# Shared conflict-magnets — every module owner reviews:
# docs/modules.yaml          @priya-gh @sam-gh @alex-gh
# .github/                   @priya-gh @sam-gh @alex-gh
